%I A395991 #17 May 17 2026 23:10:46
%S A395991 34,63,71,91,135,159,186,212,233,242,282,289,298,315,338,363,378,394,
%T A395991 436,453,477,485,508,528,565,579,606,619,643,669,693,695,716,729,751,
%U A395991 764,794,849,870,883,889,905,922,936,943,965,985,996,1029,1044,1095,1134
%N A395991 First indices of zeta zeros corresponding to Lehmer Pairs.
%C A395991 Let Z be the list of nontrivial zeros of the zeta function with the first index as 1. Let p = Z(a(n)) and q = Z(a(n)+1), then: 1/(p-q)^2 >= 1.25 * Sum_{r in Z and r!=p and r!=q} 1/(r-p)^2 + 1/(r-q)^2.
%C A395991 This sequence seems to contain every number in A326502 from 34 onwards.
%H A395991 G. Csordas, A. Ruttan and R. S. Varga, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF02142328">The Laguerre inequalities with applications to a problem associated with the Riemann Hypothesis</a>, Numer. Algorithms 1 (1991), 305-330.
%H A395991 G. Csordas, W. Smith and R. S. Varga, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01205170">Lehmer Pairs of Zeros, the de Bruijn-Newman Constant, and the Riemann Hypothesis</a>, Constr. Approx. 10 (1994), 107-129.
%H A395991 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/LehmersPhenomenon.html">Lehmer's Phenomenon</a>
%H A395991 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lehmer_pair">Lehmer pair</a>
%e A395991 The 34th and 35th zeta zeros are 1/2+i*111.0295... and 1/2+i*111.8746..., let's call them p and q. Then 1/(p-q)^2 = 1.4001....
%e A395991 Sum_{r in Z and r!=p and r!=q} 1/(r-p)^2 + 1/(r-q)^2 = 0.79....
%e A395991 Multiplying the sum by 1.25 gives 0.99...
%e A395991 And since 1.4001... >= 0.99... so 34 is in the sequence.
%Y A395991 Cf. A114886, A254297, A326502.
%K A395991 nonn
%O A395991 1,1
%A A395991 _Jwalin Bhatt_, May 13 2026
